Target file: src/editor/widget.rs.

Implementation outline:
- In the editor key event handler, add a binding for Ctrl+Shift+D.
- Obtain current selection range from the document model. Assume an API like:
  - doc.selection(): Range { start: Position, end: Position }
  - doc.has_selection(): bool
- Behavior with no selection:
  - Identify current line via cursor.line().
  - Get full line text including newline (or manage newline insertion separately).
  - Insert a copy of that line immediately after the current line index.
  - Keep cursor on the original line, preserving its column, or optionally move to the duplicated line depending on existing UX conventions; follow PRD by preserving relative position to duplicated content (i.e., if cursor was on column c of the original, after duplication keep it on column c of the line that was originally active, not moved).
- Behavior with selection:
  - Extract text for the selection range.
  - Insert duplicated text at selection.end.
  - Update selection to cover the newly inserted text, preserving a similar shape (start' = old_end, end' = old_end + len(duplicated_text)).
  - Cursor should be at the end of the duplicated block but selection still active.
- Ensure operation participates in the undo/redo history as a single atomic edit.

Pseudo-code:
```rust
if key == 'D' && event.ctrl && event.shift {
    let sel = doc.selection();
    if sel.is_empty() {
        let line = doc.cursor().line();
        let line_range = doc.line_range(line);
        let line_text = doc.text(line_range.clone());
        doc.insert_text(line_range.end, &line_text);
        // cursor stays on original line
        doc.set_cursor(LineCol { line, col: cursor_col });
    } else {
        let text = doc.text(sel.clone());
        let insert_pos = sel.end;
        doc.insert_text(insert_pos, &text);
        let new_end = insert_pos + text.len();
        doc.set_selection(Range { start: insert_pos, end: new_end });
    }
}
```

Target file: src/editor/widget.rs.

Implementation outline:
- Add keybindings for Alt+Up and Alt+Down in the editor key event handler.
- Determine affected line range:
  - If no selection: affected_lines = [cursor.line(), cursor.line()].
  - If selection: expand selection to full line boundaries encompassing selection.start.line..=selection.end.line.
- For moving up:
  - If the first affected line is 0 (top of document), do nothing.
  - Otherwise, remove the block of text for the affected lines and reinsert it starting one line above.
- For moving down:
  - If the last affected line is the last document line, do nothing.
  - Otherwise, remove the block and reinsert one line below.
- Update cursor and selection:
  - If there was no selection: move cursor line index up or down by 1, preserve column.
  - If selection existed: shift selection line indices by ±1, and keep same columns.
- Ensure operation is atomic for undo/redo.
- Consider multi-cursor support if present; if not, explicitly operate on the primary caret.

Pseudo-code:
```rust
fn move_lines(delta: isize) {
    let (start_line, end_line, had_sel, sel_cols) = doc.selection_line_span();
    if delta < 0 && start_line == 0 { return; }
    if delta > 0 && end_line == doc.last_line() { return; }

    let block_text = doc.text_for_lines(start_line..=end_line);
    doc.delete_lines(start_line..=end_line);
    let new_start = (start_line as isize + delta) as usize;
    doc.insert_lines(new_start, &block_text);

    // update selection and cursor
    let new_end = new_start + (end_line - start_line);
    if had_sel {
        doc.set_selection_lines(new_start, new_end, sel_cols);
    } else {
        let cur = doc.cursor();
        doc.set_cursor(LineCol { line: (cur.line as isize + delta) as usize, col: cur.col });
    }
}
```

