Editor behavior in src/editor/widget.rs:
- In the text input handler (on character insertion), when auto_close_brackets is true:
  - Define a mapping of opener to closer: `('(' -> ')', '[' -> ']', '{' -> '}', '"' -> '"', '\'' -> '\'', '`' -> '`', "**" -> "**", "__" -> "__")`.
  - For single-character openers: on typing an opener:
    - If there is a non-empty selection: wrap selection with opener/closer.
    - Else: insert opener+closer and move cursor between them.
  - For multi-character pairs like ** and __:
    - Detect when user types the second `*` or `_` in a pair (e.g., previous char also `*`).
    - If there is a selection: wrap selection with the pair.
    - Else: insert the full pair and move cursor between them.
  - Skip-over behavior: when user types a closing character (e.g., `)`, `]`, `}`, `"`, `'`, '`', `*`, `_`) and the next character in the buffer is the same closer:
    - Prevent inserting another character and instead move cursor one position to the right.
- Edge cases:
  - Inside existing quotes/brackets, avoid inserting duplicates for `"` based on simple heuristic: if the character before the cursor is a word character and next char is not whitespace/closing, treat typed `"` as literal; otherwise auto-close.
  - For backticks, support ``` pairs similarly to other delimiters; for triple backticks, keep current behavior for fenced blocks if already implemented.
- Ensure the auto-close logic is integrated before generic insertion so it can decide whether to override the default insertion.

Pseudo-code (simplified):
```rust
if settings.auto_close_brackets {
    if let Some(pair) = opener_for_char(ch) {
        let sel = doc.selection();
        if !sel.is_empty() {
            doc.wrap_selection(sel, pair.open, pair.close);
        } else {
            doc.insert_text(cursor_pos, &format!("{}{}", pair.open, pair.close));
            doc.set_cursor(cursor_pos + pair.open.len());
        }
        return; // prevent default insertion
    }

    if is_closer(ch) {
        let next = doc.char_at(cursor_pos);
        if Some(ch) == next {
            doc.set_cursor(cursor_pos + ch.len_utf8());
            return; // skip over
        }
    }
}
insert_char_default(ch);
```

Target file: src/editor/widget.rs (or centralized paste handling code if present).

Implementation outline:
- Intercept paste events in the editor component:
  - Use existing platform abstraction for clipboard paste (e.g., on_paste(text: String)).
- URL detection:
  - Define a helper `fn is_url(s: &str) -> bool` that checks:
    - Starts with `http://` or `https://`, OR
    - A more general regex-like pattern: `[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9+.-]*://`.
  - Define `fn is_image_url(s: &str) -> bool` that checks file extension (.png, .jpg, .jpeg, .gif, .webp, .svg, .bmp) case-insensitively.
- Behavior with selection:
  - If `is_url(pasted)` is true and there is a non-empty selection:
    - Let selected text be `label`.
    - Replace selection with `format!("[{}]({})", label, pasted)`, preserving any existing markdown context.
  - Cursor should land after the inserted link.
- Behavior with no selection:
  - If `is_image_url(pasted)` is true:
    - Insert `format!("![]({})", pasted)` at cursor position.
  - Else if `is_url(pasted)` is true:
    - Insert the URL text as-is (normal paste), as per PRD.
  - Else:
    - Fallback to default paste behavior (insert text as-is).
- Ensure operation integrates with undo/redo as a single edit.

Pseudo-code:
```rust
fn on_paste(pasted: String) {
    let sel = doc.selection();
    if !sel.is_empty() && is_url(&pasted) {
        let label = doc.text(sel.clone());
        let link = format!("[{}]({})", label, pasted.trim());
        doc.replace_range(sel, &link);
    } else if sel.is_empty() && is_image_url(&pasted) {
        let img = format!("![]({})", pasted.trim());
        doc.insert_text(doc.cursor_pos(), &img);
    } else {
        insert_default_paste(pasted);
    }
}
```

Target files: src/ui/window.rs, src/app.rs.

Implementation outline:
- Reproduce:
  - Run Ferrite on Linux Mint (or similar compositing window manager) and observe cursor behavior near the custom title bar close button.
- Code analysis:
  - Inspect custom window frame implementation in src/ui/window.rs and any related hit-test logic in src/app.rs.
  - Identify zones:
    - Title bar drag area.
    - Close/minimize/maximize button hit areas.
    - Window resize borders.
  - Look for overlapping rectangles or multiple cursor updates per frame that can cause flicker.
- Fix strategy:
  - Ensure hit-test order prioritizes window controls (close button) over resize zones.
  - Refactor cursor update logic to compute desired cursor once per pointer move event:
    - Start with default arrow.
    - If inside close button rect → set pointer to default or hand, and mark event handled.
    - Else if in resize border → set resize cursor.
    - Else if in draggable title bar → set move cursor if required.
  - Avoid rapid toggling by:
    - Caching last cursor type; only call platform API to change cursor if it differs from current.
    - Debouncing or coalescing pointer-move events if the toolkit supports it, though likely unnecessary if hit-test is correct.
- Validate that close button click handling remains correct and resize zones are unaffected.

Pseudo-code:
```rust
fn on_pointer_move(pos: Point) {
    let mut desired = CursorIcon::Default;
    if close_button_rect.contains(pos) {
        desired = CursorIcon::Default; // or Pointer
    } else if in_resize_zone(pos) {
        desired = CursorIcon::NwseResize; // etc.
    } else if title_bar_rect.contains(pos) {
        desired = CursorIcon::Move;
    }

    if desired != self.current_cursor {
        window.set_cursor(desired);
        self.current_cursor = desired;
    }
}
```
